<br>
Free speech means that the Dixie Chicks get to say they are unhappy with President Bush.  Free speech also means that other people get to say that it's unpatriotic for the Dixie Chicks to say that.  And freedom also means that those people are free to burn Dixie Chicks albums (their own, I would hope) in protest, and are free to announce that they will no longer listen to radio stations that play Dixie Chicks music.  And I am free to think the whole thing is a tempest in a teapot, and to ignore the protesters and to continue listening to the Dixie Chicks.  <br>
<br>
Free speech means you are free to speak.  Someone else may not like what you choose to say, and may choose to dislike you for saying it.  (That's called freedom of association, and guess what, it's in the same constitutional amendment.)  Free speech doesn't mean that when you speak you are free of all consequences.  <br>
<br>
And for anyone who truly believes that free speech used to be a lot freer, my own view is that you don't have a particularly thorough appreciation of U.S. history.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=agnol>agnol</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:pink;'>Tavern Floor Sweeper</span></span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(5/16/03 1:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3251.topic&index=60>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> And Agnol sayeth &quot;There shall be a subject line!&quot;</span><hr size=1> Vainne:<br>
