style='color:yellow;'>Tavern Ale Swiller</span></span><br>  Posts: 73<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(5/16/03 4:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3251.topic&index=66>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Kida</span><hr size=1> &quot;The problem is the law can be &quot;&quot;&quot;intrepeted&quot;&quot;&quot; by any moron with a license to practice law. Judges can place their views into interpreting the law also. A shitload of laws need to be more detailed and cover a broader scope so NO INTERPRETATION can be interjected. Start with Felony Murder and work your way down.&quot;<br>
<br>
Essentially, what you are talking about is a &quot;code&quot; jurisdiction, where everything is written into the law and there is (supposedly) no room for interpretation.  Louisiana is the only U.S. state that operates that way, France does as well.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, interpretation is necessary when you are operating under a code as well.  It's intrinsic to language, two people can use the same word and understand it to mean different things.  A code system narrows the range of interpretation, but it does not eliminate interpretation entirely.  <br>
<br>
Moreover, it was &quot;interpretation&quot; of the law (really, interpretation of the Constitution, but that's where the right to free speech comes from anyway, which is what we are talking about) that eliminated school segregation, that stopped coerced confessions by forcing the police to warn you of your right against self-incrimination, and that gave you many other &quot;basic&quot; rights.  <br>
